        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Keplerian orbital speeds around UX Tau A (M = 1.5 M_solar) are about 2.6-7.3 km/sec over the radial range 200 AU-25 AU, and the inclination likely lies in the range 35-60 degrees (sin i = 0.57-0.50). So the full width of spectral lines from the Keplerian disk is about 8 km/sec. Thus we have chosen 0.1 km/sec resolution (122 kHz); we could smooth considerably if necessary to improve signal-to-noise in the inner disk. The two target molecular lines are in opposite sidebands; we have specified a 2 GHz continuum band in each along with the spectroscopy basebands. 

In order to estimate the continuum sensitivity on UX Tau A, we scale the intensities observed at a nearby frequency with SMA (Andrews et al. 2011) to the smaller ALMA beam (0.13 arcsec diameter vs. 0.30 arcsec x 0.28 arcsec), under the prudent assumption that there is no structure on smaller scales than in the SMA image. This yields a peak continuum brightness of 7 mJy per beam. For the CO and HCO+ lines, we can estimate the brightness scale by comparison to the ALMA images of the transitional disk around the SU Aur star HD 142527 (Casassus et al. 2013). On the inner rim of this disk the peak brightness in CO J = 3-2 was 0.8 Jy per beam, and in HCO+ J = 4-3 was 0.2 Jy per beam. Scaling from the beamsize used in these observations (0.55 arcsec x 0.33 arcsec) reduces this by a factor of 0.079, again under the prudent assumption that there is no structure on smaller scales than the beam used for HD 142527. Scaling for the lower luminosity (3.5 vs. 15 L_solar) and the smaller Rwall (25-71 AU vs. 140 AU) in UX Tau A increases the brightness by factors of 1-1.6. This leads to estimates of 0.02-0.10 Jy/beam for the peak line brightness. Noting that this is likely to be a substantial underestimate due to the beamsize scaling, and noting that we can smooth over several spectral channels in most cases to improve S/N, we will adopt 0.1 Jy/beam and aim for a noise level a factor of 20 smaller, which would reveal all corresponding structures in UX Tau A that were detected in HD 142527. This yields a continuum sensitivity of 27 microJy/beam -- a factor of 65 more sensitive per beam than the SMA maps -- and a dynamic range in the continuum image of 250.
 
These choices lead to a total estimated time of 4.55 hours, for the automatically-chosen water-vapor column of 0.658 ppmm. Going higher in water vapor column by an octile or two would not change the time request by very much. 

</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
