    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>We propose to use the ALMA 12 m array in Band 7 to observe CO, HCO+ and continuum emission in UX Tau A. This object is one of the nearest and best examples of a pre-transitional disk -- one with a planet-carved gap separating optically-thick inner and outer disks -- and is the only one among the paradigms of this class to have a large mass fraction of crystalline grains. ALMA represents a substantial improvement in angular resolution and sensitivity over previous submillimeter instruments, and these improvements are necessary to determine key structural parameters -- gap radius, inclination, disk mass, star mass, surface density profile -- which in combination with Spitzer-IRS data can enable precise and accurate modelling. 

With the gap well resolved by ALMA, we will search for molecular emission and the kinematic signature of cross-gap accretion bridges, which would indicate the location of the infant planet(s) that carved the gap. We will also seek molecular and continuum emission from patterns within or outside of the outer disk -- such as spiral density waves and tidal tails -- in search of the origin of the anomalously large mass fraction of processed dust therein. </prp:abstract>
